A chairde,

T=E1 s=FAil agam go bhfuil sibh go maith!

Our 'Seanfhocal' for this week was: 'Cleachtadh a dh=E9anann m=E1istreacht'

Practice makes mastery. Most people are familiar with the Modern English pr=
overb, =93Practice makes perfect.=94 It connotes the trials and tribulation=
s of repeated efforts to learn a new task well. It conjures up the image of=
 the beginning musician struggling to learn the cords of her instrument. Pe=
rhaps, it evokes the scene of a budding Gaeilgeoir listening to a tape of s=
poken set phrases and repeating them over and over again.
But there is another subtle semantic variation of this week=92s proverb tha=
t is better captured in the Old English version of this proverb, =93Use mak=
eth mastery.=94 Here the English word =91practice=92 like the Irish word =
=91cleachtadh=92 has another meaning. It also means experience. In this sen=
se, mastery comes from doing. The maestro masters his instrument by perform=
ance, not just through the repetition of practice exercises. The Gaeilgeoir=
 becomes fluent not from just doing her lessons regularly but by using the =
language.
Monday night:

  *
We finished our first tense, 'An Aimsir Laithreach' (the present tense), fr=
om the slides attached.
  *
We then went through our 11 Irregular Verbs in the Aimsir Laithreach! Also =
attached.
  *
Finally we completed pages 38-39 of the book with the questions on page 39-=
40 suggested for homework!

Go raibh m=EDle maith agaibh and feicfidh m=E9 sibh ar an Luan (I will see =
you all on Monday!)

Le gach dea-ghu=ED,

Laoise Nic =CDomhair

Oifigeach Forbartha Gaeilge, Barr na gCnoc

Ionad na Gaeilge Labhartha  | Col=E1iste na hOllscoile Corcaigh | Corcaigh =
| =C9ire
