Practice makes mastery. <span style=3D"font-weight: 500;">Most people are f=
amiliar with the Modern English proverb, =93Practice makes perfect.=94 It c=
onnotes the trials and tribulations of repeated efforts to learn a new task=
 well. It conjures up the image of the
 beginning musician struggling to learn the cords of her instrument. Perhap=
s, it evokes the scene of a budding Gaeilgeoir listening to a tape of spoke=
n set phrases and repeating them over and over again.</span></div>
<div style=3D"text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; margin: 0px; padding-bott=
om: 1em; font-family: Aptos, Aptos_EmbeddedFont, Aptos_MSFontService, Calib=
ri, Helvetica, sans-serif, serif, EmojiFont; font-size: 12pt; color: black;=
" class=3D"elementToProof">
<span style=3D"font-weight: 500;">But there is another subtle semantic vari=
ation of this week=92s proverb that is better captured in the Old English v=
ersion of this proverb, =93Use maketh mastery.=94 Here the English word =91=
practice=92 like the Irish word =91cleachtadh=92
 has another meaning. It also means experience. In this sense, mastery come=
s from doing. The maestro masters his instrument by performance, not just t=
hrough the repetition of practice exercises. The Gaeilgeoir becomes fluent =
not from just doing her lessons
 regularly but by using the language.</span></div>
